04536nam a22005775i 9780300162387DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t19911991ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001623877 a10.12987/97803001623872doi  a(DE-B1597)486341  a(OCoLC)1059251872  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aLB1140.25.J3bT63 1989eb 7aEDU0000002bisacsh04a372/.21/09512191 aTobin, Joseph J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPreschool in Three Cultures :bJapan, China, and the United States /cJoseph J. Tobin, Dana H. Davidson, David Y. H. Wu. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[1991] 4c©1991  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Komatsudani: A Japanese Preschool -- t3. Dong-feng: A Chinese Preschool -- t4. St. Timothy's: An American Preschool -- t5. A Comparative Perspective -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs the numbers of mothers in the workforce grows, the role of the extended family diminishes, and parents feel under greater pressure to give their children an educational headstart, industrialized societies are increasingly turning to preschools to nurture, educate, and socialize young children. Drawing on their backgrounds in anthropology, human development, and education, Tobin, Wu, and Davidson present a unique comparison of the practices and philosophies of Japanese, Chinese, and American preschool education and discuss how changes in childcare both reflect and affect larger social change.   The method used is innovative: the authors first videotaped a preschool in each culture, then showed the tapes to preschool staff, parents, and child development experts. Through their vivid descriptions of a day in each country's preschools, photographs made from their videotapes, and Chinese, Japanese, and American evaluations of their own and each other's schools, we are drawn into a multicultural discussion of such issues as freedom, conformity, creativity, and discipline.   In China, for example, preschools are expected to provide an antidote to the spoiling that Chinese fear is inevitable in an era of single-child families. Americans look to preschools not only to teach reading and to encourage children to be creative, expressive, and independent but also to provide a stability and richness otherwise missing from many children's lives. Japanese preschools, surprisingly for many Americans, deemphasize discipline and academics and instead stress the teaching of group interaction to a generation of overly sheltered children. In all three nations, preschools, rather than being radical or transforming, function to conserve values believed to be threatened by social change.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aEducational anthropology. 0aNursery schoolszChinavCase studies. 0aNursery schoolszJapanvCase studies. 0aNursery schoolszUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aDavidson, Dana H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWu, David Y. H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packagez978311064968008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package Archivez978311053801440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300162387423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300162387.jpg  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook Package Archive  a978-3-11-064968-0  Asian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Package  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles